stitution that lies at the center of our lives.Offering an account that is more realist than utopian, Pettit starts from the function the polity is meant to serve, looks at how it can best discharge that function, and explores its ability to engage beneficially in the life of its citizens. This enables him to identify an ideal of statehood that is a precondition of justice. Only if states approximate this functional ideal will they be able to deal with the perennial problems of extreme poverty and bitter discord as well as the challenges that loom over the coming centuries, including climate change, population growth, and nuclear arms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAmendment.  aAttempt.  aAuthor.  aAwareness.  aCharles I of England.  aCitizenship.  aCivil disobedience.  aColonialism.  aCommercial bank.  aCommodity.  aConsideration.  aConsumer protection.  aContract theory.  aContract.  aContractual term.  aCorporate Agent.  aCurrency.  aDecentralization.  aDecision-making.  aDefendant.  aDemocracy.  aDirective (European Union).  aDiscretion.  aDissident.  aDoctrine.  aEmployment.  aEquality before the law.  aExplanation.  aFourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution.  aGilbert Ryle.  aIOU.  aImpunity.  aIncome.  aInflation.  aInquiry.  aInstitution.  aInstitutional theory.  aInternalization.  aIntimidation.  aJohn Locke.  aJoint-stock company.  aJust-so story.  aLaissez-faire.  aLaw.  aLegal personality.  aLegislation.  aLegislator.  aLegislature.  aLibertarian Party (United States).  aLocal community.  aLoyal opposition.  aMajority.  aMarket economy.  aMental property.  aMetaphor.  aMethodology.  aMinarchism.  aMoney supply.  aMultitude.  a